WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello everyone, my name is Maria and today I will be talking about the Power of Prototyping.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:16.000
Let me start with a short introduction. I am a Senior Delivery Manager at Epsilon,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:21.000
which in practice means that I am supporting our clients in creating new products

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.000
or enhancing tools that already exist. I am working mostly with big corporations

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.000
where we are creating internal tools for their teams.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:37.000
One of the most important aspects of my job is to support our team to create successful tools.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:42.000
For me, a tool is successful if, first of all, it is being used.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Because only if this first condition is met, we can talk about your product bringing value.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Today I will be talking mostly from my own personal experience.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:59.000
I would like to start with a short story. You can see a spoiler here, it won't be a success story.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.000
It started as a typical project.

00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:08.000
There was a manager who had this great idea for a new tool that he wanted to introduce for his colleagues.

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
He started development on his own.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:16.000
After a year, he realized that he would need some help from more experienced developers

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:21.000
to fix a few bugs and also implement more complex features.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:26.000
He decided to contact us. We started working together, but he was our only point of contact.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:31.000
He was the one deciding on the priorities. He was also validating our work.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:37.000
This is why we asked him a few times if it would be possible for us to talk with the users,

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:43.000
mostly to understand the product better, but also maybe to suggest some improvements.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:47.000
But this manager was very hesitant about it.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:51.000
He always repeated, not yet, let's finish this one additional functionality,

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.000
or let's improve this one small feature.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:58.000
So we continued the development.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.000
After an additional three months, we released the first version of the application.

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Only then we started talking with the users.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
We were able to meet with them to see how they are interacting with the application

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.000
and also ask them a few questions.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
As a result of those meetings, we prepared a report.

00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:21.000
Here you can see the result of this report.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:26.000
Nine out of ten people had problems with usability.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:31.000
In the end, they told us that they won't be using the application in the current state.

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:35.000
On the next slide, you can see a few more detailed comments, but they are quite similar.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:38.000
People were mentioning that the app is overcomplicated

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:43.000
and it is very hard to use it without proper training.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:46.000
After over a year of development altogether,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:49.000
we created something that people were not going to use.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:54.000
As you can guess, the project was closed and the app was never really on the production.

00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Of course, after a project like this, we started asking ourselves,

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
what could we have done better?

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
The first answer that we had is that we should probably talk with the users sooner.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Of course, even before contacting us, this manager could have some talks with the users.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:12.000
He could just deploy the first version of the application

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.000
and ask them to provide feedback,

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:18.000
but maybe also we could be more pushy when asking for contact with the users.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.000
That's why currently when I'm starting any project,

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:28.000
this is the one phrase that I'm trying to follow

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
and I'm trying to convince all of the clients to release as fast as possible.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
To be able to do this, you need to start simple.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
For me, the best way to be able to release fast is to start with a prototype.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
When I say prototype, I mean the first version of your application

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.000
with only a few main functionality fully developed,

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
but it is important here to focus on the default user path.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.000
Whenever you have your business case,

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
just focus on the one main thing you want your users to be able to do in your application

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:02.000
and then strip it out of everything else.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
There are, of course, some things that can be mocked

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.000
to just show to the users that it is possible to implement it,

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
but it does not need to be fully functional.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Because only then you can have something that you can show to your users

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
in just a few weeks rather than a few months.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Now, some of you may ask me,

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:24.000
what is this amazing tool that you are using to have prototype in just a few weeks?

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:28.000
In our case, especially for data-driven applications,

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Shiny would be the tool that we are using.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:35.000
There are probably many reasons that a lot of people from the Shiny team could share,

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
but for us it is, first of all, the fact that you can prototype very fast.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So, you don't need to have any web development knowledge.

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:48.000
It is enough to know R and Shiny will take care of everything else for you.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
The second point is that you have a lot of out-of-the-box packages

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:54.000
like bslib that was just presented.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:57.000
And also there are even ready-to-use templates that you can download

00:04:57.000 --> 00:04:59.000
like on our apps and on our webpage you can find some of them.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.000
And then there can be your starting point.

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:08.000
Another point is that you can deploy very fast in Shiny.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:09.000
It is very easy to deploy your app,

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
especially if you have Post-it Connect and it's just one click of a button,

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
but there are also alternatives there.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
And the last point that, in my opinion, is underappreciated

00:05:19.000 --> 00:05:21.000
is the ease to show the real data.

00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:24.000
And, of course, on one side you have a lot of ready-to-use components

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:28.000
that are allowing you to create an interactive application

00:05:28.000 --> 00:05:32.000
that your users can use to explore the data,

00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:35.000
but also we can pre-process the data directly in R.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
So, you don't need to have any additional tools

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:41.000
and we all know that usually when we are starting our project

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:46.000
the data is not perfect and it needs some cleanup or modifications.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.000
And I would like to focus a bit more on this last point

00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
and tell you why I think that it is important to show the real data to the users

00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:56.000
when you are even just prototyping.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:06.000
So, first of all, it allows the users to focus on the functionalities

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.000
rather than discussing the data in accuracy.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:15.000
So, I've been in a situation that I had to present a prototype with only mock data

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:19.000
and it still brought value, but we spent a lot of time discussing

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
why this 15 is not 17.

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:26.000
And even if I explained to the users that the data is mocked,

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:31.000
then I had to explain myself where do I plan to take the data from.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:35.000
So, in the end they were just focusing on this one part.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:40.000
Another point is that it is just easier to compare to the current process.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
So, whenever you are introducing a new tool in your organization

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:50.000
you are probably trying to support or even replace a process that already exists,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
maybe this is just sending an Excel file to your manager.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:57.000
But then if you are showing the users the same data in both places,

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:01.000
they can easily compare those two ways of doing the same task

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.000
and give you a better feedback.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:10.000
And the last point is that it allows to select the best way to present the data.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:15.000
So, we all know that if we would use some default sets like Iris,

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:17.000
your data will look probably decent.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:21.000
But then when you are starting to use production data, it may differ a lot.

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:26.000
So, one of the examples I have is that we created a big table in one of my projects

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
with rows and cells colored based on some business logic.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:33.000
And it looked very well with the mocked data, we were very happy with it.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:36.000
But then when we started using the production data,

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.000
the colors were all over the place, it was just not possible to read this

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
and we had to completely redesign this feature.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:49.000
So, let's now assume that we were able to build a prototype,

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:53.000
we are even able to show the real data.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
So, what is next?

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
So, next we need to start talking with the users.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:05.000
And today I will be talking about two ways of gathering user feedback

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:08.000
that worked best in my project.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:12.000
So, I will start with user interviews and then I will go to user workshops.

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:18.000
So, when I say user interviews, I mean a set of one-on-one meetings

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:20.000
between the users and the interviewer.

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:25.000
And here it is important, first of all, for the meetings to be really one-on-one

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:29.000
because only then the user can fully focus on the application

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:33.000
and also answer honestly for questions.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:37.000
So, if his manager is in the room, it will be a bit more difficult sometimes to do so.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:43.000
The second point is that the user has to interact with the application.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:46.000
So, this is not us showcasing the app and just explaining new features,

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:51.000
it is just sending a link to a user and asking them to perform some actions.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:55.000
And it is good to keep the instructions as simple as possible.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:58.000
So, for example, avoid saying something like,

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:03.000
could you please go to the page three and just edit data in the row four.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:05.000
It is much better to focus on this business aspect.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:08.000
So, for example, asking something like,

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.000
could you please modify the number of chamomile shampoos

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
in the magazine in Chicago in November.

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:19.000
Because then you can see how easy or difficult it is first for the user

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:22.000
to find the information about this chamomile shampoo,

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:24.000
but then also to modify it.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:29.000
And another point is to limit explanations to minimum.

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:31.000
And it may be challenging at first,

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
especially if you see people struggling with the app,

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:35.000
you want to help them.

00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:39.000
But it is crucial to just observe and learn from it.

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:44.000
And the last point here is to remember to give opportunities

00:09:44.000 --> 00:09:46.000
to provide open feedback.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:50.000
So, one thing that I'm always doing is I'm asking the users

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:53.000
to speak aloud about the thinking process.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:57.000
Because then they can tell me not only what they are doing and why,

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:00.000
but they are also sharing their expectations quite often.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:02.000
And this is a great source of information

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:05.000
on how we can improve your application.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:08.000
And also after this first part of the interview,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:11.000
so after the user stopped interacting with the application

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:12.000
and performing those tasks,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:16.000
it is good to save some time to ask additional questions.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
And here the only rule is to just avoid suggesting the answer.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:23.000
So, I would avoid questions like,

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:27.000
don't you think that this functionality is great or the most useful?

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:30.000
It is much better to ask which of the functionalities

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:31.000
is the most useful.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:35.000
Or even better, how often are you going to use

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
different functionalities here?

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
So, this was the first part about those one-on-one meetings,

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:41.000
user interviews.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:45.000
And now I will go to the second part about user workshops,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:50.000
which is a set of meetings with a larger group of users,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:55.000
ideally five to seven, but I think ten is still manageable.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:56.000
And all those meetings,

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
people are working with the application individually.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:02.000
They are then sharing their experience,

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:08.000
which is later discussed, and some improvements are suggested.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:09.000
And on those meetings,

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:15.000
it is good to split into sessions focused on one functionality.

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:22.000
Here you can see an example agenda from a workshop I did a few months back.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:26.000
I just replaced the functionality names with placeholders.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:31.000
And you may be surprised that for each functionality,

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:36.000
we have two hours dedicated.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:40.000
And it may seem a lot, especially that those are quite simple things,

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:43.000
like editing the data or even filtering it.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
But it was really needed,

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
mostly because a lot happens during these two hours.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
So, first of all, there is some individual work.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
We are sending the link to the users,

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:58.000
and we are asking them to, again, go through the app,

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:01.000
to focus on this one particular functionality,

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
to perform the tasks that they would normally do.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
And then I am also in the room answering questions,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
looking how they are interacting with the app.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:13.000
So, it is quite similar to what I described before.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:14.000
But then during this process,

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:19.000
they have time to note down some feedback that is later discussed,

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:22.000
prioritized, and then, again, discussed.

00:12:22.000 --> 00:12:24.000
So, you can imagine that if there is like 10 people in the room,

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:28.000
probably the discussion can take some time.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:32.000
And another point is to give an easy way to provide feedback.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:34.000
But you should also think about yourself here,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:39.000
to make it easy later for you to gather it and summarize it.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
What we usually do is,

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:44.000
we are preparing for every separate functionality

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:45.000
to be a board like this,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:50.000
with the things that people liked in a given functionality,

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:51.000
they didn't like,

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
the things that are missing and are obligatory,

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:56.000
they have to have them to be able to use the app,

00:12:56.000 --> 00:12:57.000
and the things that are missing

00:12:57.000 --> 00:13:02.000
and can be implemented later somewhere in the future.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:07.000
What I also started doing is that I also created another space

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
called parking lot,

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
that people can add some random thoughts that they had in mind,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
just to not interrupt during each session.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:22.000
And the last point is to save some time to prioritize.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:26.000
So, after all of the sessions,

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:29.000
it is good to have additional one to just take,

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:34.000
you know, three to five cards from every board like this,

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:36.000
put them, again, in one place,

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:40.000
and prioritize them and discuss this prioritization.

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
And this discussion is extremely important.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:46.000
So, for example, I've been in a situation that,

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:48.000
you know, after this exercise, I looked at the cards,

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
and I saw that something that I thought is super important

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:54.000
based on the conversations was somewhere at the bottom.

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:58.000
So, I asked the users, why is this the case?

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
And they told me that this is obvious,

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:02.000
that it needs to be implemented.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.000
And it wasn't obvious for me.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:06.000
So, it would probably not be that obvious

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:09.000
for the development team as well.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:12.000
That's why I think this time to talk about it

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
is very important.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:16.000
And usually the results of such workshops

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:19.000
are just a report with a list of priorities

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
and a short description about each priority,

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:27.000
sometimes also if you can add some simple visuals

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:30.000
that can help.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:32.000
And this report is later also very useful

00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:33.000
during the development.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:34.000
So, if you have reviews with the users,

00:14:34.000 --> 00:14:36.000
you can even go back to it.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:37.000
You can discuss it and show them

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
that you are listening to them

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
and trying to implement the improvements.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:45.000
And I told you at the start that user workshops

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
and user interviews work best in my projects.

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
So, now I want to just defend it a bit.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:55.000
So, first of all, it allows for a detailed discussion,

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
something that I mentioned, I think,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
a few times during this talk.

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
But because of this, you can understand

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:05.000
not only what people want you to do, but also why.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:09.000
And then you can suggest some alternatives.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
But also have a bigger picture

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:14.000
and make sure that when you are designing a new feature,

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.000
you are taking this into consideration.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:21.000
So, both in the architecture, but also in the UX design.

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:25.000
Another point is that you need only five to ten users,

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:27.000
which I think is not a lot.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:28.000
One thing to remember here

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
is that this group should be diverse.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
So, if you are building something

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:34.000
that should work across departments,

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:37.000
probably you should have people from different departments.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:41.000
The same from people from different regions.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:45.000
And I would like to finish my talk with another story,

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
this time a success story.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:49.000
And it started in the same way.

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
So, there was this manager with this big, amazing idea

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:57.000
for a new tool that he wanted to introduce in his organization.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.000
And he needed our help to develop it.

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
So, we learned from our experience.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
So, even before starting a project,

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
we talked with him to be able to have

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
some users involved in the process.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:12.000
But fortunately, he was very open for this.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
He not only was talking with the users a lot about the product,

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
but also he was open for us to have those discussions.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:22.000
What is more, he agreed to start with a prototype.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.000
So, just after three weeks, we already had something

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:28.000
that we could present to the users and discuss with them.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:31.000
We decided to go with the user interviews

00:16:31.000 --> 00:16:34.000
because it was still when COVID was there.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.000
So, we had to do it online.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:40.000
And the results of these interviews were not as horrible

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:42.000
as the ones that I showed you before.

00:16:42.000 --> 00:16:46.000
But we learned that one of the main functionalities

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:50.000
is not working in a way that people are expecting it to work.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
In the end, it wasn't a huge change from the UI perspective,

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:56.000
but it was big enough change that we had to

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.000
redesign the data architecture.

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
So, imagine this happening five months into development.

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:05.000
It would be a real big change that would influence a lot of features.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
So, we continued the development.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:10.000
And after just additional five months,

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:14.000
we were able to deploy the first version of the application.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:16.000
And the feedback was very positive.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:18.000
People were excited about it.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:21.000
Currently, the app is used by thousands of users.

00:17:21.000 --> 00:17:25.000
And we are still adding new features.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:30.000
So, to summarize my talk,

00:17:30.000 --> 00:17:33.000
if you want to build a new product

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
and not go bankrupt,

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
involve the end users early on,

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
release fast,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:45.000
and don't forget about using the real data.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:47.000
So, if you want to talk more,

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
feel free to reach out to me on LinkedIn.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:52.000
I would be happy to discuss the projects that you are doing

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:54.000
and also your challenges.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
And here, I also wanted to thank Posit for inviting me.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:18:00.000
And thank you all for joining here today.

00:18:07.000 --> 00:18:09.000
Thank you, Maria.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:12.000
We have time for one quick question,

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:16.000
which sort of aims at the advice to release fast.

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:20.000
Do you have any advice on how to balance doing that

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:22.000
and making a good impression?

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:26.000
I think the best advice I would give

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:29.000
is to just start with a group of users that you trust

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
and you know that will be open to seeing a tool

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
that is not perfect.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
Because in the end, it won't be.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
And it will be buggy.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:39.000
It won't work perfectly.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.000
It probably won't be the prettiest

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:43.000
if you want to be asleep.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:46.000
So, you can always start with people that you trust

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:48.000
and people that you know are open

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:50.000
to seeing things that are not ideal.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:51.000
Thank you.

